        "Tafseer": "1. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nIndeed, We have granted you a clear triumph. (1)\n\nSome Aspects of the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah Being a 'Clear Triumph'\n\nBy 'clear triumph' (fathan mubeena) here is meant the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah; there is no room to interpret this as any other victory. Some aspects of its being a clear triumph are entirely obvious. For example:\n\n* First, this was the first time that the Quraysh openly accepted the Muslims' right over the House of Allah (Ka'bah), and this acceptance was not as a favor, but because they were subdued by the Muslims. Below, verse 24 will make it clear that if the treaty had not been made and war had broken out, the victory of the Muslims was certain. The Quraysh had estimated the situation well; because of this, they were desirous of the treaty in their hearts. However, to keep their nose high, they wanted the Muslims not to insist on performing the Umrah that very year, but to come the subsequent year. To make the Muslims agree, they even offered a great incentive—that they would completely evacuate the city for three days so that there remained no fear of any conflict. This offer from the Quraysh was no ordinary thing.\n\n* Second, the Quraysh, by virtue of this treaty, accepted the Muslims as their equal rival power in Arabia. In their eyes, the Muslims' status was no longer of rebels and traitors, as they had openly said until then, but of a political power of equal rank; thus, they openly accepted for them the right that whichever tribe of Arabia wished to become their ally could do so.\n\n* Third, the Quraysh also acknowledged the Muslims' military capability to the extent that they themselves insisted on including the condition of a ten-year truce in the treaty.\n\n* Fourth, on this occasion, the reason why Allah Almighty did not give His Prophet and the Muslims permission for battle was not because of any weakness on the part of the Muslims, but only because there were many apparent and hidden Muslims in Makkah who had not been able to migrate. There was a fear that in case of battle, they would suffer harm at the hands of the Muslims themselves. \n\nIn short, the various aspects of its being a clear triumph were obvious and could not remain hidden from the Muslims; but the Quraysh showed their ancestral pride (hamiyyat-al-jahiliyyah) in such a way, and some highly provoking events—for example, the event of Abu Jandal—occurred during this, that a general feeling arose among the Muslims that this treaty was being made under duress. In the heat of emotions, people could not reflect on every aspect of the treaty to estimate what they had achieved and what they had lost. When this Surah drew attention to the actual realities, only then did people realize that in reality they had committed a mistake in understanding the implications of the treaty, and when its results appeared, everyone saw with open eyes that this treaty indeed proved to be the introduction to the Conquest of Makkah."
