    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 2,
        "Tafseer": "\"That Allah may forgive for you what preceded of your sin and what will follow and complete His favor upon you and guide you to a straight path And [that] Allah may support you with an Exalted support.\" (2-3)\n\nSome Results of This Clear Triumph\n\n'La' (That/So that) here is used in the sense of the final result—meaning: this clear triumph which Allah has bestowed upon you is the introduction which will end upon the subsequent matters with which Allah Almighty is going to bless you.\n\n* First, now that time is near when you will be relieved of the responsibilities of your mission, and Allah Almighty will forgive all your past and future lapses to bless you with His mercy.\n\n* Second, Allah Almighty is going to complete His favor upon you.\n\n* Third, Allah Almighty will open the correct path of guidance for you.\n\n* Fourth, Allah Almighty will grant you such dominance as cannot be challenged.\n\nAll of these four matters are mentioned briefly here. To understand them well, there is a need to explain them in the light of the parallels in the Qur'an.\n\n'That Allah may forgive for you what preceded of your sin and what will follow': This gives the Prophet (pbuh) glad tidings that after this clear triumph, the time for being relieved of the responsibilities of messengership has drawn near. This theme has passed in various styles in the Qur'an. For example, in Surah An-Nasr:\n\n'When the victory of Allah has come and the conquest, And you see the people entering into the religion of Allah in multitudes, Then exalt [Him] with praise of your Lord and ask forgiveness of Him. Indeed, He is ever Accepting of repentance.' (1-3).\n\nWithin this Surah, along with the glad tidings of victory and dominance, there is also the indication that after this, the time for being relieved of the responsibilities of messengership will draw near; but instead of giving glad tidings in clear words, instruction was given to prepare for it—stating: prepare for it with glorification, prayer, and asking for forgiveness. In the verse under discussion, this same theme has occurred as a highly clear glad tidings under the requirement of the context. The meaning is: this clear triumph which you have achieved is the introduction; after this, the time is near when your Lord will relieve you of the responsibility He had placed upon you, and will relieve you with such complete vindication and sarp-frazey that He will forgive all your past and future lapses. No greater glad tidings could belong to the Prophet (pbuh) than this: that Allah Almighty would relieve you of the great mission He had entrusted to you in such a way that no minor or major responsibility remained upon you, but you achieved the assurance that you performed this duty precisely in accordance with the will of your Lord. In this clause, you have been granted this very certificate of His pleasure.\n\nAnd obviously, no greater certificate could exist for you. In gratitude for this, in the final period of his life, when his worship increased extensively, people asked him: 'O Messenger of Allah, all your past and future lapses have been forgiven, so why do you bear such hardship in worship?' You replied: 'Then, should I not be a grateful servant?'\n\nThe Nature of Lapses Committed by the Prophets\n\nRegarding the 'sin' (dhanb) attributed here to the Prophet (pbuh), we have been clarifying in various places: the Prophets (peace be upon them) never committed lapses of the nature of following desires, but in their efforts for establishing religion, under their zeal, sometimes such matters were committed by them upon which Allah Almighty took them to account. For example, the hypocrites came to the Prophet (pbuh) and fabricated excuses to be excused from participating in Jihad. You knew that they were making excuses, but due to your noble nature, you excused them so that they were not humiliated. This soft approach of yours, although the result of your noble nature, containing no trace of following desires, was taken to account by Allah, because a prophet is the touchstone of truth and justice in every matter. For this reason, he must not exceed that limit in dealing with people which Allah has appointed.\n\nSimilarly, the Prophet (pbuh) sometimes showed more care to the chiefs of his nation—thinking: if they believed, they would become a source of strength and progress for the invitation. This is not a sin in itself, but a highly important requirement of the interest of religion; but if it becomes so much as to lead to negligence regarding the rights of those who truly deserve care, or to increase the arrogance of the unworthy, then Allah Almighty stops His Prophet from it. The event of the blind man described in Surah 'Abasa is of this very nature.\n\nSimilar events occurred in the lives of other prophets, which we have explained in their proper places. In the verse under discussion, the lapse attributed to the Prophet (pbuh) is of this very nature. Regarding all such matters, you have been given glad tidings that they will be forgiven.\n\n'what preceded... and what will follow' are terms primarily used to express all-encompassing nature. But they also show: the lapses committed before this glad tidings are forgiven, and also if any lapse is committed after it, it is included in this command. For this, no new glad tidings is required.\n\n'and complete His favor upon you'—this is glad tidings of the completion and perfection of the favor of religion. Thus, on the occasion of the Farewell Pilgrimage, when this favor was completed, this declaration was made: 'This Day I have perfected for you your religion and completed My favor upon you and have approved for you Islam as religion.' (Al-Ma'idah: 3).\n\nThe Fruit of the Completion of the Favor of Religion\n\n'and guide you to a straight path'—this describes the fruit of the completion of the favor of religion: Allah Almighty will guide you to that straight path from which Satan had turned people away. It should be clear: the religion which Allah Almighty sent down for the guidance of creation was lost by the Jews and Christians as well, and the Arab polytheists had also turned the center of Tawhid constructed by Hazrat Ibrahim and Hazrat Ismail (peace be upon them) into an idol-temple, due to which the straight path of guidance was completely lost. This path was opened anew for creation when Allah Almighty renewed and completed His religion through the Prophet (pbuh), and the center of Tawhid constructed by Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him) emerged from the block of disbelief in its actual Ibrahimic beauty. In this clause, this reality is pointed to—showing that now the religion will stand manifest and that center of light will be unveiled which was constructed to guide to the actual highway of guidance.\n\nHere, this glad tidings is given addressing the Prophet (pbuh). This same glad tidings is given in verse 20 addressing all Muslims. There, we will shed further light on it.\n\nThe True Meaning of 'an Exalted support' (Nasran Aziza)\n\nBy 'an Exalted support' (Nasran Aziza) is meant such victory and help against disbelief as cannot be challenged. Obviously, such support can be achieved only when the power of disbelief is completely broken. In other words: when the power of the Quraysh is completely ended and the House of Allah comes into the control of the Muslims. Until then, the successes achieved by the Muslims against the Quraysh were indeed important, but they were not such as could not be challenged. As long as the Quraysh were dominant over Makkah, they were indeed a power; but the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah shook this power of theirs, and the time was not far when the old structure of their authority would collapse in a single shock. This is that very Exalted support of which glad tidings is given. 'Aziz' means dominant and powerful, and also 'manee'' (unreachable)—meaning that to which no one else has access.\n\nThe Eloquence of the Sequence\n\nIn the sequence of these glad tidings, there is also an eloquence: the thing which is to appear first in the future is mentioned at the very end, and the thing which is the summary of all and will appear at the very end is mentioned first. This is the sequence of sending down—meaning in describing the contents, the sequence chosen is of descending, not of ascending. In our view, the reason is that this was the occasion to give glad tidings to the Prophet (pbuh); the glad tidings of the Conquest of Makkah was indeed important, but a greater, rather the greatest glad tidings for you was to place before you that reward of the Hereafter which you are to receive, and in whose receiving there is no delay remaining."
