        "Tafseer": "\"It is He who sent down tranquility into the hearts of the believers that they would increase in faith along with their [present] faith. And to Allah belong the soldiers of the heavens and the earth, and Allah is Knowing and Wise.\" (4)\n\nProof for the Promise of Support\n\nThis presents proof for the promise of support mentioned in the preceding verse—showing: it is of His help that He placed within the hearts of the believers this resolve to accompany you for the Umrah, so that they may increase in faith through this resolve and their accompanying the Prophet.\n\nIt should be kept in mind: although this journey was for the Umrah, the Prophet (pbuh) resolved upon it in highly dangerous conditions. A state of war with the Quraysh was ongoing, and until then, their passion was such that they continuously launched attacks against Medina; in such conditions, it could not be expected in any way that if the Muslims went as a group for the Umrah, they would easily let them enter Makkah without any resistance. Thus, the subsequent verses will make it clear that the hypocrites assumed: the Muslims are going into the mouth of death, and they will never return from this journey. In such conditions, for fourteen or fifteen hundred companions to leave their homes and set out for a journey of two hundred and fifty miles, entirely unarmed, was no ordinary thing; but Allah Almighty blessed their faith, sent down resolve upon them, and they set out. The meaning is: the God Who blessed your companions with this resolve on this occasion will also encourage them in subsequent stages, and the Exalted support He is promising will be fulfilled.\n\nThe Trials Faced by the Believers are for Testing Their Faith\n\n'that they would increase in faith along with their [present] faith' (liyazdadoo imanan ma'a imanihim) points to that wisdom of religion: the trials which the believers face in this world are in reality for testing their faith. If they succeed in this test, their faith increases in strength, until they achieve the station of 'the soul at peace', and if they fail, and continuously fail, their light of faith is completely extinguished.\n\nThe Correct Aspect of Imam Abu Hanifah's (ra) View regarding the Increase and Decrease of Faith\n\nThis is a requirement of the Sunnah of Allah, and this Sunnah naturally requires that faith is a thing that increases and decreases. If it had been a static thing, this test was not required. As for what is attributed to Imam Abu Hanifah—that he did not believe in the increase and decrease of faith—it has a specific context. By this, his objective was that legal and formal faith upon which a Muslim's civic rights are established in an Islamic state, and not that faith upon which the ranks of the Hereafter are based. In terms of legal and formal faith, every Muslim who accepts the essentials of religion is equal, and the Islamic state will deal with everyone as a Muslim. In this aspect, there will be no difference between a Bedouin and a city-dweller. As for the Hereafter, its success is based on true faith, whose knowledge is with Allah Almighty alone, and He alone will judge it. In our view, this view of the Imam is correct, but it is often advocated wrongly, and critics have not tried to understand his point.\n\nThose Who Help the Prophet open the Way of Success for Themselves\n\n'And to Allah belong the soldiers of the heavens and the earth, and Allah is Knowing and Wise'—meaning: Allah's preparing of the believers to accompany you was His favor upon them so that they increase their faith through this virtue; otherwise, He stands in no need of anyone to help His Prophet and His religion. All the powers and armies of the heavens and the earth are under His control; He can take retribution from the disbelievers through these armies of His whenever He pleases, but He invited the believers to help His Prophet so that He opens for them the way to achieve a great success. Allah is Knowing and Wise. His every action is based on knowledge and wisdom, and in this action of His also lies His great wisdom. If further details are required, have a look at what we wrote under verse 4 of Surah Muhammad."
