    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 5,
        "Tafseer": "\"[And] that He may admit the believing men and believing women into gardens beneath which rivers flow to abide therein eternally and do away with their misdeeds - and that is ever with Allah a great attainment -\" (5)\n\nThe Reward of the Increase in Faith\n\nThis describes the reward of 'liyazdadoo imanan ma'a imanihim' above, and the style is of describing a consequence. The meaning is: He opens the ways of increasing their faith so that He admits the believing men and believing women into gardens beneath which rivers flow, wherein they will abide eternally, and He will remove their lapses from them—meaning this is no losing bargain, but is entirely gain.\n\nA Question and Its Answer\n\nHere, a question might arise: the entry into Paradise is mentioned first, and the removing of lapses is mentioned after it, whereas people will enter Paradise after their lapses are removed? In our view, this sequence is apparent. To highlight the glad tidings, the entry into Paradise is mentioned first, and the objective is to say: Allah will purify them of lapses and admit them to Paradise.\n\nSatire on the Hypocrites\n\n'and that is ever with Allah a great attainment'—meaning in the sight of Allah, the true and greatest success is this; so blessed are those who, to achieve this success, played the game of life regardless of all dangers. This is an introduction to the mention of the hypocrites which is coming, and whose state was described: out of fear of the Quraysh, they sat in their houses and assumed that their policy was successful and they saved themselves from a great danger through their cleverness; whereas they did not save themselves, but cast themselves into destruction, of which they will soon become aware."
