    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 8,
        "Tafseer": "5. Subsequent Theme: Verses 8–21\n\nIn the subsequent verses, the Prophet's (pbuh) status is clarified first. Then, the rights of the Prophet (pbuh) established upon the believers by virtue of his status, and the responsibilities which lay upon them by virtue of their pledge of allegiance at his hands, are clarified. Then, the attitude of those hypocrites who stayed in their houses making false excuses is commented upon. They did not set out for the Umrah out of fear that the Muslims would never return. Then, those selfless Muslims are mentioned who pledged allegiance to the Messenger of Allah (pbuh) under highly difficult conditions, and as a reward for their sincerity, became deserving of His eternal pleasure and His help in the world... Recite the verses.\n\n6. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"Indeed, We have sent you as a witness and a bringer of glad tidings and a warner That you [people] may believe in Allah and His Messenger and support him and respect him and exalt Him morning and afternoon.\" (8-9)\n\nDescription of the Prophet's Status\n\nAddressing the Prophet (pbuh), He stated: We have sent you as a witness to Our religion, and as a bringer of glad tidings and a warner. As a witness—meaning as a witness to the religion of Allah before the people, showing what We command Our servants to do and what We forbid them from. At the same time, He has sent you to give the glad tidings of Paradise to those who accept your testimony to reform their lives, and to warn those of the punishment of Hell who deny your testimony or do not give it its due importance. Although this is said as a general rule, the subsequent discussions will show that the target are those hypocrites who verbally accepted the Prophet's (pbuh) messengership, but sought ways to escape from its requirements.\n\nThe Meaning of 'Witness' (Shahid)\n\n'Shahid' means a witness—meaning a witness to the religion of Allah before the people. Generally, people have interpreted this as the testimony you will give in the Hereafter, but in our view, this is incorrect. The testimony which the Prophets (peace be upon them) will give in the Hereafter is because they established testimony to the religion of Allah in this world. We have discussed this under verses 45-47 of Surah Al-Ahzab. The testimony which the Prophets (peace be upon them) will give in the Hereafter has been discussed in detail in Surah Al-Ma'idah.\n\nThe Objective of the Prophet's Advent, and His Right upon the Ummah\n\n'That you [people] may believe in Allah and His Messenger and support him and respect him and exalt Him morning and afternoon'—addressing the Muslims, He stated: We have sent Our messenger as a witness, a bringer of glad tidings, and a warner so that you believe in Allah and His Messenger, help the Messenger and respect him, and exalt Allah in the morning and afternoon. Believing in Allah and His Messenger refers to true faith. After this, in an ascending order—meaning from below to above—those requirements of faith are described which are self-evident. The requirement of faith in the Messenger is: become his helper in his efforts for establishing the religion of Allah, and respect and honor him as His messenger. Then, the requirement of faith in Allah is: continuously exalt Him in the morning and afternoon.\n\nCorrecting a Misconception of the Commentators\n\nGenerally, people have considered 'support him' (tu'azziroohu) and 'respect him' (tuwaqqiroohu) as relating to Allah Almighty. In their view, if the referent of the object pronoun is assumed to be the Messenger, a distance is produced. In our view, this is based on a misconception. Here, the order is ascending, as we pointed out; therefore, no distance is produced. After demanding faith in Allah and His Messenger, the right of the Messenger was described first because his mention was at the end; therefore, his right was described conjoined with his mention, and after this, the right of Allah Almighty was described. This order is chosen in various places. If 'tu'azziroohu' and 'tuwaqqiroohu' are not assumed to relate to the Prophet (pbuh), some deficiencies will appear in the discourse, from which the discourse must be pure. For example:\n\n* First, this verse is in the context of describing the rights of the Prophet (pbuh), expressing the objective of why Allah Almighty sent the Prophet (pbuh) as a witness, a bringer of glad tidings, and a warner. If this interpretation is accepted, the verse remains empty of mentioning his rights and is cut off from the context.\n\n* Second, the target are the hypocrites, whose primary weakness was that despite claiming to believe, they were devoid of obeying the Prophet (pbuh), helping him in Jihad, and respecting him (as will follow in the subsequent Surah). This required that they were told of these requirements of faith. If they are assumed to relate to Allah Almighty, the verse will become disconnected from its context.\n\n* Third, 'ta'zeer' (supporting/helping) and 'tawqeer' (respecting/honoring) are not suitable for Allah Almighty; they are suitable only for the Messenger. 'Tuwaqqiroohu' is entirely unsuitable for Allah Almighty. 'Tu'azziroohu' has also occurred in the Qur'an only for the messengers, never for Allah. See verse 12 of Surah Al-Ma'idah and verse 157 of Surah Al-A'raf. Under verse 25 of Surah Muhammad, have a look at what we wrote. There are many verses in the Qur'an where different verbs are used, and the verb itself determines its subject or object. This is a matter of the taste of the language. If this is not kept in view, great misconceptions can arise."
