    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 10,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you - they are only pledging allegiance to Allah. The hand of Allah is over their hands. So he who breaks his word only breaks it against himself, and he who fulfills what he has covenanted with Allah - He will give him a great reward.\" (10)\n\nThe Responsibilities of the Pledge of Allegiance at the Messenger's Hands\n\nThis is a further tayeed of the preceding theme—showing: those who pledge allegiance to you to hear and obey should remember that they do not pledge allegiance to you, but in reality to Allah. At the time of the pledge, the hand over their hands is not yours, but Allah's. If they, after pledging allegiance, avoid its responsibilities and break their word by their deeds, they should remember: the consequence of it will fall upon them alone, because the actual party of this covenant is Allah, and no one can harm Allah. The one who is unfaithful to Him only harms himself; and it must also be remembered: whoever fulfills the responsibilities of this covenant will never remain in loss, but will receive a great reward with Allah. Generally, people have assumed this verse to relate specifically to the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, whereas it has no specific relation to it. The Treaty of Hudaybiyyah (Bi'at-ar-Ridwan) will be mentioned in verse 18. This mentions that general pledge of allegiance to hear and obey which every believer made at the hands of the Prophet (pbuh). Its grandeur and responsibilities are described to warn the hypocrites—showing: they pledged allegiance at the Messenger's hands, but when the time came to fulfill its demands, they hid. The reality is clarified: pledging allegiance at the Messenger's hands is in reality a covenant with Allah. If anyone avoids its responsibilities, he breaks his covenant with Allah, and its end is disgrace in both this world and the Hereafter.\n\nAnswering a Grammatical Doubt\n\nIn this verse, regarding the vowel (dhammah) on the pronoun in 'alayhu-llah' (with Allah), some orientalists have criticized the grammar of the Qur'an. These poor people do not know that the books of grammar are no touchstone to evaluate the Qur'an's style; but the Qur'an is the touchstone to evaluate the books of grammar. The Qur'an is the highest example of the standard language of the Quraysh, and is protected from every aspect; therefore, if anything in it appears contrary to the makhraj of the grammarians, we will not criticize the Qur'an, but attribute it to the deficiency of the grammarians.\n\nIn eloquent Arabic, purely due to the requirements of rhythm and form, such تصرفات have occurred upon letters, words, and pronouns that if a person's knowledge is limited only to books of grammar, he cannot encompass them. Take pronouns: there are several examples in the Qur'an where the pronoun has been completely absorbed within the word. For example, in verse 111 of Surah Al-A'raf: 'Arjih wa-akhah' (Delay him and his brother). Similarly, in verse 52 of Surah An-Nur: 'yakhsha-llaha wa-yattaqih' (fears Allah and fears Him).\n\nJust as this vowel appears strange to people in the verse under discussion, exactly this is the case in verse 63 of Surah Al-Kahf: 'wama ansaneehu illa-sh-Shaytan' (and no one made me forget it except Satan). We do not intend to list all examples here. Those who seek details of this issue will find many examples in the Surahs of the final group showing that purely due to the requirements of rhythm, the form of letters, words, and pronouns has undergone such changes for which grammarians can find no explanation. Such is the case here."
