    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 11,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those who remained behind of the Bedouins will say to you, 'Our properties and our families kept us busy, so ask forgiveness for us.' They say with their tongues what is not in their hearts. Say, 'Who then could limit [power to protect] you from Allah at all, if He intended for you harm or intended for you benefit? Rather, Allah is ever, of what you do, Acquainted.'\" (11)\n\nExposing the Hypocrites\n\nNow, this actual point is described for which the preceding preface was made. It states: when you return in safety from this journey, those among the Bedouins who were left behind will come to you with false excuses—claiming: 'the responsibilities of managing our properties and families kept us busy, so show compassion on our difficulties to pray to Allah Almighty for our forgiveness.' Their excuse does not deserve attention. They say with their tongues what is not in their hearts.\n\n'Say, \"Who then could limit [power to protect] you from Allah at all, if He intended for you harm or intended for you benefit?\"'—meaning ask them: 'If you have such concern for your interests that you ignore His rights, then tell us: if God intends some harm or benefit for you, who will stand against Him!'\n\n'Rather, Allah is ever, of what you do, Acquainted'—meaning do not try to hide under such excuses. Allah is fully aware of all your deeds.\n\nThe Meaning of 'Mukhallaf'\n\nFor these hypocrites, the word 'mukhallaffoon' (those left behind) is used—meaning those who were left behind, whereas they stayed behind of their own accord. The reason was explained under Surah At-Tawbah—showing: when they decided that staying behind was their wise policy, Allah also threw them back: 'So when they deviated, Allah deviated their hearts' (As-Saff: 5)—meaning these people did not stand to step forward due to their cowardice; because of this, God also pushed them back. These people belonged mostly to the villages around Medina; because of this, the word 'A'rab' (Bedouins) is used, which is well-known.\n\nIn 'Who then could limit [power to protect] you from Allah at all' (Faman yamliku lakum minallahi shai'an), 'yamliku' (limit/protect) encompasses the meaning of preventing, and the preposition 'min' is its indicator. We have opened this."
