        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 12,
        "Tafseer": "\"But you thought that the Messenger and the believers would never return to their families, and that was pleasing to your hearts. And you assumed an assumption of evil and became a ruined people.\" (12)\n\nThe True Secret of the Hypocrites' Hearts\n\nThis explains that secret of their hearts pointed to in the preceding verse—showing: 'The actual thing which prevented you from this journey was your assumption: now the Quraysh will completely consume these Muslims, and neither they nor their Prophet will ever see their families again.'\n\n'and that was pleasing to your hearts. And you assumed an assumption of evil'—meaning since this assumption was beloved to you, you appreciated it in your hearts and it was made attractive to you. Then, under its influence, you made bad assumptions regarding the future of Islam—assuming that its story was going to end within a few days.\n\n'and became a ruined people'—meaning you remained waiting for the destruction of Islam and the Muslims, but Allah Almighty blessed them with a clear triumph; and you, who boasted that by not accompanying the Prophet you adopted a successful policy, prepared your own destruction."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 13,
        "Tafseer": "\"And whoever has not believed in Allah and His Messenger - then indeed, We have prepared for the disbelievers a Blaze.\" (13)\n\nAllah's Decision regarding the Hypocrites\n\nThis is Allah's decision regarding these hypocrites—stating: those who, while claiming to believe, show such cowardice in performing His rights and desire the destruction of Islam, do not believe in Allah and His messenger, but are disbelievers; and these disbelievers must remember that We have prepared for them Hell."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 14,
        "Tafseer": "\"And to Allah belongs the sovereignty of the heavens and the earth. He forgives whom He wills and punishes whom He wills. And Allah is ever Forgiving and Merciful.\" (14)\n\nAnd they must also remember: no other protector will save them from His grasp. The sovereignty of the heavens and the earth is in the control of Allah alone; no other has any share in His sovereignty to affect His decisions. He will forgive whom He pleases, and punish whom He pleases.\n\n'And Allah is ever Forgiving and Merciful'—meaning everyone must remain assured: Allah is Forgiving and Merciful. He does not desire to punish His servants, but to show mercy to them. For this reason, people must adopt the path of His pleasure which He has opened through His Prophet, instead of seeking false supports."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 15,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those who remained behind will say when you set out to war booty to take it, 'Let us follow you.' They wish to alter the word of Allah. Say, 'Never will you follow us. Thus has Allah said before.' So they will say, 'Rather, you envy us.' But they do not understand except a little.\" (15)\n\nOn this occasion, these cowardly people stayed in their houses making excuses; but in the future, when such opportunities arise where you are expected to receive war booty without any fight, they will come claiming to accompany you so that they also receive war booty without any danger. It states: tell them when such an opportunity arises: 'You can never accompany us. Allah has commanded this before.'\n\n'when you set out to war booty to take it' points to those bootees of Khaybar, etc. which the Muslims received after the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah. For these bootees, the Muslims did not have to fight any major battle; rather, the enemy surrendered out of fear. The Jews of Khaybar were very wealthy; because of this, the Muslims received immense booty. 'to take it' (li-ta'khudhooha) indicates that the Muslims set out specifically to take the booty.\n\n'They wish to alter the word of Allah'—meaning these hypocrites, by offering to accompany you, wish to alter that word of Allah which He has spoken regarding them. This points to what has passed in verse 6: 'And [that] He may punish the hypocrite men and hypocrite women and the polytheist men and polytheist women - those who assume about Allah an assumption of evil. Upon them is a misfortune of evil, and Allah has become angry with them and has cursed them and prepared for them Hell, and evil is it as a destination.' The meaning is: these people wish that they do not have to perform any service for the religion, but they receive its benefits in both this world and the Hereafter; but this desire of theirs is not going to be realized. The word of Allah regarding them cannot change until they change their own condition.\n\n'Say, \"Never will you follow us. Thus has Allah said before\"'—meaning if they wish to accompany you, do not permit them; tell them clearly: 'You can never accompany us. Allah commanded this before, but you did not comply, staying in your houses.' In our view, this points to that general call of the Umrah which the Prophet (pbuh) made but these hypocrites avoided. The meaning is: when you avoided departing with the Messenger and the believers before, why are you so anxious now? Is it because you expect an easy gain now without any danger?\n\nA Misconception\n\nSome have interpreted 'Thus has Allah said before' as that statement which is mentioned in verse 83 of Surah At-Tawbah. But this is incorrect. Surah At-Tawbah mentions those hypocrites who showed cowardice on the occasion of the Battle of Tabuk. This Battle occurred long after the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, and here the reference is to some event which occurred before Hudaybiyyah, as is clear from 'before' (min qabl).\n\n'So they will say, \"Rather, you envy us\"...'—meaning although they will be highly displeased at not being permitted, and will accuse you of envy, do not care about their accusation, because they are highly short-sighted people. Due to their short-sightedness, they want to receive all benefits of religion without making any sacrifice. They must understand that such childish desires of theirs are not going to be realized."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 16,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say to those who remained behind of the Bedouins, 'You will be called to [face] a people of great military might; you will fight them, or they will submit [i.e., surrender]. Then if you obey, Allah will give you a good reward; but if you turn away as you turned away before, He will punish you with a painful punishment.'\" (16)\n\nA Test for the Hypocrites\n\nThis is a test placed before these hypocrites—showing: 'If you are indeed loyal to Allah and His messenger, you cannot prove it by seeking war booty without any danger; rather, the time is coming when you will be called to fight a group of great military might, and you will have to fight them with the resolve that they either accept Islam or the sword. If you accept this invitation and stand to fight them, Allah Almighty will bless you with a good reward, and if you show cowardice, as you showed on the occasion of the Umrah before, remember that Allah Almighty will punish you with a painful punishment.'\n\nTo Free the Ka'bah, a Decisive Battle with the Quraysh was Inevitable\n\n'a people of great military might' (qawmin uli ba'sin shadeed) refers to the Quraysh. In Arabia, only their power was such as to deserve this description. Although a treaty was made with them, to free the House of Allah from their control, a decisive battle was inevitable. The completion of the Prophet's (pbuh) mission was not possible without it.\n\nFor the Arab Polytheists, Only Two Paths Remained: Islam or the Sword\n\n'you will fight them, or they will submit'—since the Prophet (pbuh) was sent specifically to the Quraysh, and Allah Almighty fully established proof against them in their own language through him, only two paths remained for them: Islam or the sword. Other nations could be allies or Dhimmis, but there was no such allowance for the polytheists of the Children of Ismail. They could not even be made slaves. The detailed explanation of this has passed in Surah At-Tawbah.\n\n'but if you turn away as you turned away before'—meaning if you show the same cowardice on this occasion as you showed before on the occasion of the Umrah, remember that Allah Almighty will punish you with that painful punishment which He has destined for His open enemies."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 17,
        "Tafseer": "\"There is not upon the blind any guilt or upon the lame any guilt or upon the ill any guilt [for remaining behind]. And whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger - He will admit him to gardens beneath which rivers flow; but whoever turns away - He will punish him with a painful punishment.\" (17)\n\nThe Case of the Excused\n\nThis describes those excused whose absence from Jihad will not be attributed to hypocrisy. It states: there is no blame upon the blind, the lame, and the sick if they cannot participate in Jihad, provided they obey Allah and His messenger with a sincere heart. If they obey, they will not be deprived of Paradise for this forced shortcoming, but Allah Almighty will admit them to gardens; and if they turn away from Allah and His messenger, they will face that painful punishment which is destined for His enemies.\n\nThe mention of these excused has also passed in verses 91-93 of Surah At-Tawbah; have a look at them. Some of those aspects which are not clarified here have been clarified there."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 18,
        "Tafseer": "\"Certainly was Allah pleased with the believers when they pledged allegiance to you, [O Muhammad], under the tree, and He knew what was in their hearts, so He sent down tranquility upon them and rewarded them with a near conquest And much war booty which they will take. And ever is Allah Exalted in Might and Wise.\" (18-19)\n\nThe Reward of the Selfless\n\nAfter mentioning those who avoided the responsibilities of the pledge of allegiance, this describes those who, under highly critical conditions, pledged allegiance to you at Hudaybiyyah for Jihad and performed the right of this pledge. The mention of these believers began with: 'Certainly was Allah pleased with the believers'—showing that their pledge of allegiance was so valued in the sight of Allah Almighty that He announced His eternal pleasure for them; thus, in the history of Islam, this pledge of allegiance is known as 'Bi'at-ar-Ridwan' (the Pledge of Pleasure). The conditions under which they made this pledge in the very center of the enemy have been mentioned; have a look.\n\nThe Descent of Tranquility from Allah Almighty\n\n'when they pledged allegiance to you, [O Muhammad], under the tree'—traditions suggest that this pledge was made under an acacia tree. 'The tree' (Al-Shajarah) points to this tree. By this, it is intended to bring to the forefront the state of their exile and travel.\n\n'and He knew what was in their hearts, so He sent down tranquility upon them'—the number of the Muslims who participated in this pledge was no more than fourteen or fifteen hundred. Due to the restrictions of the Umrah, they were also unarmed. Purely under the requirement of religious jealousy, relying on the help of Allah Almighty, they prepared to collide with the massive power of the Quraysh. In such conditions, what state of devotion and turning to Allah must have been upon their hearts, who besides Allah can estimate? Pointing to this, He stated: Allah knew the state of their hearts and sent down tranquility and peace upon them. This was in accordance with the Sunnah of Allah which has been explained—showing that when His servants stand for Jihad in His path, though apparent conditions are highly unfavorable, the Generous Lord encourages them, and this encouragement is that actual strength which cannot be defeated by any powerful enemy.\n\nPointing to the Conquests after Hudaybiyyah\n\n'and rewarded them with a near conquest And much war booty which they will take'—this points to the conquest of Khaybar and those bootees which the Muslims received immediately after returning from Hudaybiyyah, and which established the trust in the hearts of the believers: the promises of victory He made to them are true, and the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah was not their defeat, but their clear triumph and the introduction to subsequent victories, and this near conquest will prove to be the introduction to the Conquest of Makkah.\n\nBy 'near conquest' (fathan qareeba), commentators have meant the conquest of Khaybar; this appears correct, because the conquest of Khaybar occurred immediately after returning from Hudaybiyyah.\n\n'And ever is Allah Exalted in Might and Wise'—He referred to His attributes which are the guarantee that His promises will be fulfilled. Though apparent conditions are highly unfavorable, His power and wisdom are dominant over everything."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 19,
        "Tafseer": ""
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 20,
        "Tafseer": "\"Allah has promised you much booty that you will take and has hastened for you this and withheld the hands of people from you that it may be a sign for the believers and [that] He may guide you to a straight path.\" (20)\n\nThe preceding clause was said addressing the Prophet (pbuh); this addresses the Muslims—stating: Allah has promised you much booty which you will achieve in the near future. To confirm these promises, He has hastened this booty for you so that it serves as encouragement for you and a sign of the success of Islam.\n\nBy 'hastened for you this' (fa'ajjala lakum hadhihi), commentators have meant the booty of Khaybar. This appears correct, because the conquest of Khaybar occurred immediately after returning from Hudaybiyyah.\n\n'and withheld the hands of people from you'—'people' (Al-Nas) refers to the Quraysh. In the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, both parties, the Muslims and the Quraysh, accepted the restriction that they would not launch any military action against one another for ten years. This benefited the Muslims, as they got an opportunity to launch an action against the Jews of Khaybar, and the Jews, realizing that the Quraysh's support was no longer available, lost their confidence. In this way, the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah opened the way for a near conquest for the Muslims, and proved that this treaty was not their defeat, but their clear triumph and the introduction to subsequent victories.\n\n'that it may be a sign for the believers'—the conjoined clause is omitted according to the well-known rules. That is: Allah gave this near booty to the Muslims so that it served as a proof for them of the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah's being a clear triumph, and also as a sign of the future success and dominance of Islam.\n\nGlad Tidings of the Conquest of Makkah\n\n'and [that] He may guide you to a straight path'—this has passed under verse 2, where we have explained it: this points to the reality that now that time is near when Allah Almighty will bless the Muslims with the completion of the favor of religion and open for His servants that straight path of guidance which His enemies had blocked. Since the primary sign of this straight path is the Ka'bah, within this is also the glad tidings of freeing it from the control of the disbelievers."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 21,
        "Tafseer": "\"And [He promises] another [victory] which you were not able to [achieve] - already Allah has encompassed it. And ever is Allah over all things competent.\" (21)\n\nThis points to the Conquest of Makkah. It states: another highly great success is there which Allah has promised you. Although you have not been able to achieve this success yet, there is no great delay in its achievement. Allah has encompassed it, and what is encompassed by Allah cannot escape His control. Allah is competent over everything; He will soon show this miracle of His help."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 22,
        "Tafseer": "7. Subsequent Theme: Verses 22–26\n\nNext, the Muslims are assured: if the Quraysh had initiated battle on this occasion, they would have faced defeat; but the wisdom of Allah Almighty required that this battle did not occur yet, so that no harm reached those Muslims who are imprisoned in Makkah. Within this, the moral superiority is highlighted which the Muslims achieved on this critical occasion against the disbelievers, and which proved that the life of the Quraysh's ancestral pride is now very short. Recite the verses.\n\n8. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"And if those who disbelieve had fought you, they would have turned their backs; then they would not find a protector or a helper.\" (22)\n\nIf Conflict Had Occurred, the Quraysh's Defeat Was Certain\n\nThis is consolation for the Muslims and a warning to the Quraysh—showing: the cause why He did not permit you for battle on the occasion of Hudaybiyyah was not because there was any fear of your defeat. If battle had occurred, they, not you, would have turned their backs, and would have been defeated in such a way that they would find no helper or protector to support them. For this reason, there is no cause for them to show pride and consider this treaty as your weakness; rather, they must remain grateful to God that He gave them some respite to reflect on the situations."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 23,
        "Tafseer": "\"The way [i.e., Sunnah] of Allah which has occurred before. And never will you find in the way of Allah any change.\" (23)\n\nThe Sunnah of Allah regarding the Deniers of the Messengers\n\nThis points to that Sunnah of Allah which He has appointed for the deniers of the messengers—showing: when their cup is filled, such punishment falls upon them that they find no refuge anywhere, and this Sunnah is so certain and inevitable that no change ever occurs in it. The entire history of the messengers is witness to this."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 24,
        "Tafseer": "\"And it is He who withheld their hands from you and your hands from them within Makkah after He caused you to overcome them. And ever is Allah, of what you do, Seeing.\" (24)\n\nWhatever Occurred on the Occasion of Hudaybiyyah Occurred by Divine Planning\n\n'within Makkah' points to Hudaybiyyah. This is at the very border of Makkah; because of this, it is described as 'within Makkah'.\n\nThat is: the fact that battle did not occur on this occasion is the miracle of divine planning. Although Allah Almighty had granted you victory over them, and if battle had occurred they would have faced defeat, yet His wisdom required that this battle did not occur yet; because of this, He withheld their hands from you and your hands from them. 'And ever is Allah, of what you do, Seeing'—meaning Allah Almighty was Himself evaluating all situations; therefore, whatever occurred occurred in accordance with His wisdom, and in it lies your own benefit.\n\nThe Muslims' Resolve Weakened the Quraysh's Confidence\n\n'after He caused you to overcome them'—meaning in terms of the moral aspect, your superiority was prominent, and in terms of resolve, you dominated them. It should be clear: when the Quraysh came to know of that passion of the Muslims which they showed in pledging allegiance to the Prophet (pbuh), their confidence was shaken. Thus, they immediately sent an embassy to initiate talk of peace. This embassy indeed tried to maintain their pride, but it was clear that they did not possess the strength to fight the Muslims; thus, they accepted in the treaty of their own accord: next year when the Muslims come for the Umrah, they will evacuate Makkah for three days so that there remains no fear of any conflict."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 25,
        "Tafseer": "\"They are the ones who disbelieved and averted you from the Sacred Mosque and the offering, prevented from reaching its place of sacrifice. And if not for believing men and believing women whom you did not know - lest you trample them and there befalls you from them a sin [i.e., crime] without [your] knowledge - [you would have been permitted to enter]. [This was] so that Allah might admit to His mercy whom He willed. If they had been apart [i.e., separated], We would have punished those who disbelieved among them with a painful punishment.\" (25)\n\nThe Wisdom of Not Letting Battle Occur\n\nThis describes the wisdom of why Allah Almighty did not let battle occur on this occasion—showing: although the Quraysh's offenses were open, as they disbelieved, turned the believers away from the Sacred Mosque, and prevented the offerings brought for sacrifice from reaching their place of sacrifice; yet, despite all these insolences and offenses, His wisdom required that the believers did not draw their swords against them yet. The primary reason was: there were many believers, both men and women, in Makkah whom the Muslims did not know, and there was a fear that if they had attacked, these oppressed believers would have also suffered harm, which would bring upon them the blame of shedding their own brothers' blood. The second was: among these people of Makkah were many who, though they had not believed yet, were close to belief. Allah Almighty willed to admit them into His mercy.\n\n'If they had been apart, We would have punished those who disbelieved among them with a painful punishment'—meaning if these believers had been separated from them, Allah Almighty would have punished the disbelievers of the Quraysh with His painful punishment.\n\nBy 'painful punishment', the Muslims' attack can be meant, and also some such punishment as came upon previous nations. In their stories, you have read: when they denied the messenger, Allah Almighty separated the believers from among them and destroyed the entire nation.\n\nRemoving a Doubt\n\nFrom this verse, it is learned: if the Muslims have to fight any nation in which are also Muslims, they must try to ensure that the Muslims suffer no harm. However, if the enemy tries to benefit from this—for example, if they make the Muslims fight against the Muslims or use them as shields, or the Muslims themselves stand to fight the Muslims due to some national bias or worldly interest—in such conditions, the collective interest of Islam and the Ummah must be kept, even if some group of Muslims suffers harm.\n\nPointing to a Grave Insolence of the Quraysh\n\nIn the verse, 'offering' (hadya) with 'prevented' (ma'koofan) is to express the gravity of the situation—showing: although this action of the Quraysh was highly insolent—preventing the offerings brought for the Creator from reaching their place of sacrifice—yet, His wisdom required that they were not punished for this insolence yet, so that no harm reached those Muslims who were besieged in Makkah.\n\nThe apodosis of 'Law' (If) is omitted, and this omission is proof of His intensity of anger. Precedents have passed. Below, 'If they had been apart...' (Law tazayyaloo) has opened this omission.\n\n'whom you did not know - lest you trample them'—'an tata'oo' (lest you trample them) serves as an appositive (badal) to the pronoun 'hum'—meaning: there was a fear that you would remain unaware of trampling them, and thus, without your knowledge, your own brothers' blood would be shed by your own hands."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 26,
        "Tafseer": "\"When those who disbelieved had put into their hearts chauvinism - the chauvinism of the time of ignorance. But Allah sent down His tranquility upon His Messenger and upon the believers and imposed upon them the word of righteousness [i.e., piety], and they were more deserving of it and worthy of it. And ever is Allah, of all things, Knowing.\" (26)\n\nIn Highly Critical Conditions, the Muslims Proved Their Moral Superiority\n\nThis explains the moral superiority of the Muslims—showing: although the Quraysh showed their ancestral pride (hamiyyat-al-jahiliyyah) at every step, which could incite the Muslims, yet Allah Almighty blessed His Prophet and the Muslims with the capability to deal with these critical conditions with patience, peace, and wisdom; they did not take any action under the influence of the opponents' conduct which was contrary to the pleasure of Allah and the interests of religion.\n\n'Tranquility' (Sakeenah) refers here to patience, peace, gravity, wisdom, and planning. In collective life, such stages often arise when the wisdom of a group is tested. On such occasions, if the group takes any hasty action under the influence of emotions, it harms the primary objective irreparably. It is only of the guidance of Allah that a group and its leader succeed in such tests, and this is achieved by those who remain connected with their Lord.\n\nThe Display of Ancestral Pride on the Part of the Quraysh\n\n'The chauvinism of the time of ignorance' (hamiyyat-al-jahiliyyah) refers to those actions of the leaders of the Quraysh which they took contrary to truth and justice purely to keep their nose high. For example:\n\n* It was clear to them: the Prophet (pbuh) was coming only for the Umrah; there was no thought of war in his heart, nor did he have any weapons; yet, they were not ready to permit him to enter the House of Allah to present His offerings.\n\n* The ambassadors whom the Prophet (pbuh) sent to inform them of his arrival, they not only did not respect their diplomatic status, but prepared to kill one of them, and kept the other in such suspense that the rumor spread among the Muslims that they had killed him as well.\n\n* In setting the terms of the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, they created unnecessary difficulties and insisted on including those conditions which did not bring any political benefit to them, but temporarily satisfied them that their word was high.\n\nThe Knowledge and Piety of the Muslims\n\nThe natural reaction of the Quraysh's conduct upon the Muslims could be that they took some action in anger, but under the blessing of tranquility sent down by Allah, they remained pleased with the decision of Allah and His messenger.\n\n'and imposed upon them the word of righteousness [i.e., piety]' (wa-alzamahum kalimata-t-taqwa)—meaning despite all these provoking activities of the Quraysh, Allah Almighty kept the Muslims bound to the word of piety. 'The word of piety' (Kalimat-at-Taqwa) refers to the declaration of the janh-nisar companions before the Prophet (pbuh): 'We are pleased with Allah as Lord, with Muhammad as His messenger, and with Islam as religion.' This great word has always been the shield of the sincere and loyal Muslims against the whisperings of Satan and his agents. Whenever any condition arose where they felt the Prophet's word was contrary to their interest, they considered it a whispering of Satan and removed it with this admission. This great word became the shield of the Muslims on this critical occasion as well, and they remained pleased with the Prophet's decision, though their emotions and desires demanded something else.\n\n'and they were more deserving of it and worthy of it'—meaning this steadfastness on the word of piety is not achieved by every claimant, but is achieved by those who are deserving and worthy of it. Since the companions of the Prophet (pbuh) were deserving and worthy of it, Allah Almighty kept them steadfast in these critical conditions. Allah Almighty does not let the faith of His servants go to waste who value their faith and try to remain firm upon it in all conditions.\n\n'And ever is Allah, of all things, Knowing'—meaning Allah Almighty is not unaware of His servants' states. He knows the trials in which they are placed, and is fully aware of their conditions and feelings. If the servants perform the duty required of them, Allah Almighty does not leave them alone, but becomes their helper and protector in every task."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 27,
        "Tafseer": "9. Subsequent Theme: Verses 27–29\n\nNext, the concluding verses of the Surah contain, first, the clarification: the dream which the Prophet saw was entirely true. The delay in its fulfillment was based on the wisdom of Allah. After this, references are made to those prophecies of the success and dominance of Islam which are present in the Torah and the Gospel—so that the Muslims are consoled and also characterize themselves with those attributes which are described of them in previous scriptures. Recite the verses.\n\n10. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"Certainly has Allah shown to His Messenger the vision in truth. You will surely enter the Sacred Mosque, if Allah wills, in safety, with your heads shaved and [hair] shortened, not fearing [anyone]. He knew what you did not know and has made besides that a near conquest.\" (27)\n\nThe Prophet's (pbuh) Dream Was True\n\nIt has been pointed out above that the Prophet (pbuh) resolved upon this Umrah based on his dream; because of this, people expected that this journey would be successful. But when the result was contrary to their expectations, a question arose in many minds: 'The Prophet's dream cannot be wrong, so why did we have to return from this journey without success?' To answer this question, the aforementioned wisdoms of the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah were clarified. At the end, referring specifically to that dream, He stated: 'The dream which Allah showed to His Prophet is entirely true and based on truth. Its being based on truth is beyond doubt.' 'If Allah wills, you will surely enter the Sacred Mosque in safety, with your heads shaved and hair shortened, and you will have no fear of any resistance.' The meaning is: now the way of the Umrah has been cleared for you by virtue of the treaty. The only difference is: you will achieve this success next year, not this year, and this delay was not contrary to the dream. This is because there was no promise in the dream that this Umrah must occur this year. When some people presented this question before the Prophet (pbuh), you stated: 'There was no promise in the dream that we would perform the Umrah this year.' The meaning is: what was promised in the dream was not wrong, but this year the way of the Umrah was cleared so that when the Muslims come next year, they face no danger. 'In truth' (bil-haqq) relates to 'the vision' (ar-ru'ya)—meaning this dream was no ordinary dream, but was based on reality.\n\n'with your heads shaved and [hair] shortened'—shaving the head or shortening the hair is among the rituals of Hajj and Umrah. Its wisdom has been discussed. Of the two, priority belongs to shaving, but according to conditions, shortening is also permissible. Because of this, both are mentioned. The meaning is: this group will consist of both types of pilgrims who, with this prominent sign of servitude, will enter the Sacred Mosque if Allah wills, without any fear.\n\nPointing to the Wisdom of Postponing the Umrah\n\n'He knew what you did not know and has made besides that a near conquest'—this points to those wisdoms of postponing the Umrah which were mentioned in verse 25—meaning these wisdoms were not in your knowledge, but were in the knowledge of Allah; because of this, He did not prefer that you defeat the Quraysh and perform the Umrah this year, but His wisdom required that you set out for the Umrah this year so that Allah Almighty blesses you with a near conquest which opens the way for subsequent victories, and your Umrah is performed in peace and security.\n\nBy 'near conquest' (fathan qareeba), commentators have meant the conquest of Khaybar; but in my view, this refers to the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, which was described as 'a clear triumph' at the beginning of this Surah. On the blessings of this clear triumph, we have written. This near conquest proved to be the introduction to the Conquest of Makkah. The Conquest of Makkah was still some distance away, but the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, as has been explained, cleared the way for it; because of this, it was described as 'a near conquest'. As if: after this, that primary victory is about to stand manifest which, though not manifest yet, Allah Almighty has encompassed, as is pointed out in verse 21."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 28,
        "Tafseer": "\"It is He who sent His Messenger with guidance and the religion of truth to manifest it over all religion. And sufficient is Allah as Witness.\" (28)\n\nGlad Tidings of the Dominance of Islam\n\nThis verse has passed with a minor change of words in Surah At-Tawbah, and will also come in Surah As-Saff. In the commentary of Surah At-Tawbah, we explained its context and its objective. This is, in other words, the glad tidings of the Conquest of Makkah, because upon its conquest depended the dominance of the religion of truth over the entire land; thus, after its conquest, all other religions present in Arabia surrendered before Islam, and after a short time, that period arrived when the Prophet (pbuh) announced: 'Two religions cannot coexist in this land.' It states: that same God, Who has shown His glory which was described above, has sent His messenger with His guidance and the religion of truth to make it dominant over all religions. The meaning is: this is the inevitable decision of destiny; neither can the polytheists change it, nor the Jews and Christians; His decision will stand manifest against everyone. In Surah At-Tawbah, this is expressed as:\n\n'They want to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths, but Allah refuses except to perfect His light, although the disbelievers dislike it. It is He who sent His Messenger with guidance and the religion of truth to manifest it over all religion, although those who associate partners dislike it.' (32-33).\n\nIf you look at the context, you will find: in the preceding verse, the People of the Book are challenged, and in the subsequent verse, the polytheists. In the land of Arabia, the conflict of Islam was with these groups, but history is witness: as long as the Muslims remained the bearers of Islam, Allah made His religion dominant everywhere.\n\n'And sufficient is Allah as Witness'—meaning: although the opponents consider this glad tidings as far-fetched, it is a reality, and His testimony is sufficient for its truthfulness. This is said to console the Muslims—stating: do not be worried by the opponents' opposition and the unfavorable conditions. This promise of Allah will be fulfilled. What was stated with 'although the disbelievers dislike it' and 'although those who associate partners dislike it' in Surah At-Tawbah is expressed here in other words."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 48,
        "AyahNumber": 29,
        "Tafseer": "\"Muhammad is the Messenger of Allah; and those with him are forceful against the disbelievers, merciful among themselves. You see them bowing and prostrating [in prayer], seeking bounty from Allah and [His] pleasure. Their mark is on their faces from the trace of prostration. That is their description in the Torah. And their description in the Gospel is as a plant which produces its offshoots and strengthens them so they grow firm and stand upon their stalks, delighting the sowers - so that He may enrage by them the disbelievers. Allah has promised those who believe and do righteous deeds among them forgiveness and a great reward.\" (29)\n\nReference to the Prophecies of the Success of Islam in Previous Scriptures\n\nAt the end, this is a reference to those parables and prophecies which are present in the Torah and the Gospel regarding the attributes of the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions, and the success of Islam.\n\n* One objective is: to show the Muslims their picture in the mirror of previous scriptures so that they are consoled, and also characterize themselves with those attributes which Allah Almighty willed to see within them, and which are to identify them among creation.\n\n* Second: to warn the People of the Book, showing that they should not try to conceal the truth while knowing it. Allah Almighty informed them beforehand so that when the time came, they would testify. But it is of their misfortune that they stood in opposition instead of testifying.\n\n* Third: to clarify to the Muslims that Allah Almighty will indeed grant them dominance in this land, but this dominance will appear gradually. Neither should they hasten nor despair. The seed they sowed, let them continue its nurturing with patience. The time will come when Allah Almighty will make it such a great tree that a world will find refuge in its shade.\n\nPointing to a Parable present in the Torah\n\nMost translators have translated 'Muhammad is the Messenger of Allah' (Muhammadun Rasoolullah) as the subject and the predicate, but in my view, 'Messenger of Allah' (Rasoolullah) is used as an adjective or an appositive (atf-e-bayan). The predicate is 'forceful against the disbelievers...' which follows. This points to a parable in the Torah in which the picture of the entire group of believers is presented in such a way that the Prophet (pbuh) holds the position of the chief of the group. If we stop on 'Messenger of Allah' and assume 'and those with him' (walladhina ma'ahu) as the beginning of a new sentence, the beauty of the verse will be lost. The actual beauty is manifest only when the Prophet (pbuh) holds the chief position in it, as is the actual fact.\n\nSevere like a Rock, Gentle like Wax\n\n'and those with him are forceful against the disbelievers, merciful among themselves'—this describes an outstanding characteristic of yours and of your companions: they are severe like a rock against the disbelievers, and gentle like wax among themselves—meaning all their passion and non-com is for faith and Islam. Those who do not share in faith, if they wish to use them for their purposes, they will find no room to establish any hold. On the contrary, toward their brother believers, they are entirely merciful and kind. This has passed in Surah Al-Ma'idah in these words: 'humble toward the believers, powerful against the disbelievers' (54). Since these two verses share the same theme, we quote what we wrote there so that the correct meaning is clarified:\n\n'\"Humble\"' (adhillah) is the plural of 'dhaleel'. In Arabic, this word, as we pointed out under verse 123 of Al-Imran, is used in both good and bad senses. When used in a good sense, as is here, it means gentle, soft-tempered, obedient, modest, and submissive. 'Dhalool' is used in this sense. An obedient camel is called 'naqatun dhalool'.\n\n'\"Powerful\"' (a'izzah) is the plural of 'azeez'. This is the opposite of 'dhaleel'. It means severe, hard, heavy, unreachable, and difficult to subdue. If they say regarding something: 'huwa 'azeezun 'alayya', it means: 'that thing is heavy and difficult for me. Subduing and controlling it is difficult for me.'\n\nIn this connection, we have explained the meaning of 'severe against' (shadeedun 'ala) in this manner:\n\n'When a person fails to create resolve in his youth, achieving it in old age becomes highly difficult.'\n\n'The meaning is: for the Muslims, they will be highly gentle, soft-tempered, and submissive, but for the disbelievers, they will be like a rock. If the disbelievers wish to use them for their purposes, they will find no room to establish any hold. Lord Masih instructed his disciples: \"Be harmless as doves and wise as serpents,\" which also contains these two aspects.'\n\nKeep in view also: the context of the verse of Surah Al-Ma'idah is exactly the same as of the verse of Al-Fath. There we clarified: the hypocrites are warned that their character has occurred opposite to the Islamic character. What was suitable was that they were submissive toward the believers, and severe against the disbelievers. But their state is: they are like toys in the hands of the disbelievers, but are highly deceptive in dealing with the believers. Similarly, in this Surah, it will be recalled, the hypocrites' character was discussed in detail in verses 6-18. At the end, this aspect of the believers' collective character is highlighted so that the hypocrites see their face in this mirror—seeing what the character of the believers should be, and what character they are showing—waiting for a bad day for the Prophet and his companions, and going to the disbelievers to assure them: 'If any danger is faced by you, we will support you.'\n\nDue to not understanding the correct meaning of 'forceful against the disbelievers' (ashidda'u 'alal-kuffar), some fell into the misconception: Islam desires that every Muslim behaves with non-Muslims in a harsh and averse manner, whereas this is contrary to the words of the Qur'an and is supported by no action of the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions. We hope our explanation will suffice to remove this misconception.\n\nA Life Connected with Both the Creation and the Creator\n\n'you see them bowing and prostrating [in prayer], seeking bounty from Allah and [His] pleasure'—this is a depiction of their devotion, their night prayers, and their Tahajjud prayers. The meaning is: whoever looks at them will realize on the very first look that contrary to general humans, they belong to a group of godly people whose primary objective in life is to seek the pleasure of God; thus, sometimes he will find them in bowing, sometimes in prostration. In the preceding clause, their relation with creation was mentioned; in this clause, their relation with their Creator is pointed to—meaning their relation with creation is established on the correct foundation (severe against the disbelievers and gentle toward the believers), and their relation with the Creator is also highly robust (at no moment are they negligent of Him). In the sight of Allah, the approved life is only that which is connected with both the creation and the Creator on the correct foundation. If any deficiency occurs in either, the entire life becomes irregular.\n\nA Outstanding Mark of the Companions\n\n'Their mark is on their faces from the trace of prostration' points to their outstanding mark—showing that the traces of prostrations are prominent on their faces. The words clearly show that the trace which kethrat-e-sajdah produces on the forehead is meant, and it is also clear that Allah Almighty loves this mark—to the extent that He willed to identify this Ummah with this mark against other nations in this world. This is clear from the words of the Qur'an; therefore, we do not agree with those who have tried to interpret this metaphorically. We do not deny that some people try to make this mark prominent purely for show; but merely because some show this for display, the value of this outstanding mark of the believers cannot be decreased. Show is possible in every small or great work of religion.\n\nTraditions suggest that Hazrat Umar (ra) reproached some who tried to make this mark prominent. Hazrat Umar (ra) was well-informed. If he warned anyone, as a educator of the Muslims, he was justified, and this has a context. This does not decrease the value of this outstanding mark referred to in the verse under discussion.\n\nThe Jews' Distortions in Prophecies\n\n'That is their description in the Torah'—meaning the description of the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions is in the Torah. This points to those prophecies regarding the Prophet (pbuh) and his companions which are present in the Torah, the Psalms, and the books of Isaiah—though the Jews have distorted them. They immediately cut any words which they think the Muslims can use. However, today also, such things are present in the Torah and the Gospel whose مصداق can be no other than the companions of the Prophet (pbuh). For example, in Deuteronomy 33:2:\n\n'The Lord came from Sinai and dawned over them from Seir; he shone forth from Mount Paran. He came with ten thousands of holy ones; at his right hand was a fiery law for them.'\n\nThis prophecy's مصداق can obviously be no other than the Prophet (pbuh); in it, Mount Paran is mentioned, and his appearing with ten thousands of holy ones is also referred to. It should be kept in mind that here the Qur'an has referred to this prophecy in the context of the Muslims' victory and dominance—and it is a historical reality that on the Conquest of Makkah, ten thousand companions accompanied the Prophet (pbuh).\n\nOnly God knows how many distortions have occurred in this prophecy, but a fresh example is: 'ten thousands of holy ones' has been changed in some editions to 'ten lakhs' (one million) so that the Muslims cannot apply it to the Conquest of Makkah. However, reflecting on it shows that it refers to all those matters which the Qur'an has mentioned.\n\nIt refers to ten thousand holy ones. 'Holy ones' (quddooseen) obviously refers to pure-character, God-fearing, and devout servants. In the Qur'an, this has been described as: 'you see them bowing and prostrating... Their mark is on their faces from the trace of prostration.' Now, either the Qur'an has explained this term 'holy ones' of the Torah by describing their attributes so that the People of the Book recognized them; or the Torah also described these attributes, but the Jews, to conceal the prophecies, removed them and left only the word 'holy ones' so that they could interpret it as they pleased. Both are possible, but no fair-minded person can deny that the مصداق of this prophecy can be only the companions of the Prophet (pbuh).\n\nAnother specific thing in this prophecy is: 'at his right hand was a fiery law for them.' 'A fiery law' is, in our view, an expression for what has been described as 'forceful against the disbelievers' in the Qur'an. Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) expressed this as: 'His winnowing fork is in his hand, and he will clear his threshing floor, gathering his wheat into the barn and burning up the chaff with unquenchable fire.'\n\nHazrat Isa (peace be upon him) expressed this in another place as:\n\n'\"The stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone... Therefore I tell you that the kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a people who will produce its fruit. Anyone who falls on this stone will be broken to pieces; anyone on whom it falls will be crushed.\"' (Matthew 21:42-44).\n\nIn Deuteronomy 33:3, these words are also present:\n\n'Surely it is he who loves the people; all the holy ones are in his hand. At your feet they all bow down, and from you they receive instruction.'\n\nReflect on the underlined words; though translation has made the meaning obscure, this is that very same point which the Qur'an has described as: 'you see them bowing and prostrating [in prayer], seeking bounty from Allah and [His] pleasure'.\n\nReference to the Parable of the Gospel\n\n'And their description in the Gospel is as a plant which produces its offshoots and strengthens them so they grow firm and stand upon their stalks, delighting the sowers - so that He may enrage by them the disbelievers.' After the Torah's parable, this is the reference to the Gospel's parable. In the Torah's parable, the picture of the believers' devotion, their dominance, and their justice and mercy was described. In the Gospel's parable, their gradual development is highlighted—showing: although their beginning will be highly weak, they will ultimately become such a great tree that major nations will take refuge in its shade. In Matthew 13:31-32, this parable is:\n\n'He told them another parable: \"The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed, which a man took and planted in his field. Though it is the smallest of all seeds, yet when it grows, it is the largest of garden plants and becomes a tree, so that the birds come and perch in its branches.\"'\n\nThis parable is also in Mark 4 and Luke 8. The Qur'an explained this by showing: the condition of the gradual progress of Islam will be like the development of crops—when seeds are sowed in the field, first they bring forth fine offshoots, then they receive support to grow firm and thick, and the crop stands on its stalk. In the same manner, a day will come when the seed of truth sowed in Arabia will reach its full growth—which will delight its sowers, and enrage those who tried to stop its growth.\n\nIn 'so that He may enrage by them the disbelievers' (li-yagheedha bihimu-l-kuffar), 'li' (so that) is to show the consequence, and 'disbelievers' (kuffar) clarifies the actual meaning of the parable. Since the believers are meant in this parable, He clarified at the end: their dominance will ultimately be a cause of regret and envy for the disbelievers—meaning He clarified the object of the parable. In Arabic, in parables and metaphors, this is a well-known style—to clarify at the end what is meant so that the primary objective is clear. In the parable of Surah An-Nur, an obvious example is present.\n\n'Allah has promised those who believe and do righteous deeds among them forgiveness and a great reward'—this is that promise of support and forgiveness for whose establishment the prophecies of the Torah and the Gospel were referred to—stating: those who prove to be the مصداق of these attributes and are robust in faith and deeds, Allah Almighty will bless them with forgiveness and a great reward. As for those who claimed to believe but whose sympathies were with His enemies and who showed that cowardice on the occasion of the Umrah, if they do not reform their way, they will face the end destined for the opponents of Islam.\n\nBy the favor and guidance of Allah, the commentary of this Surah is completed on these lines. Praise be to Allah, Lord of the worlds.\n\nRahman Abad\n1 November, 1976 AD\n8 Dhu-l-Qa'dah, 1396 AH."
    }
]